<DOC><DOCNO> AP890517-0216 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1032EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a PM-ReligionRoundup Adv19   05-17 0542</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 19,0565</SECOND><HEAD>$adv19</HEAD><HEAD>For release Fri PMs May 19, or thereafter</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Television journalist Bill Moyers says he seesevidence of a powerful spiritual stirring in the world that makesreligion the key ``story of the next 50 years.''   He told the annual convention of the Religious Public RelationsCouncil that the search for faith, meaning and values represents amajor challenge to the news media.   Citing a record response to a series he did on the ``Power ofMyth,'' he said he now is focusing more on spiritual issues than onpolitics or international affairs.   ``It's the biggest story of the millennium,'' he said.</TEXT><DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   United Methodist Bishop Jack M. Tuell ofLos Angeles was installed as president of the denomination'scouncil of bishops at its May meeting here to serve for a one-yearterm.   He succeeds Bishop Ernest T. Dixon Jr. of San Antonio, Texas.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eighty-three Roman Catholic priests who gavetheir lives in service to their country as military chaplains arehonored in a monument to their memory in Arlington NationalCemetery.   The monument is being dedicated on Sunday. The priest-casualtiesincluded 70 in World War II, six in Korea and seven in Vietnam.Among them, 68 were Army chaplains, 14 Navy and one Air Force.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A recent poll in Israel found that 61 percent ofthe people oppose legal changes advocated by Orthodox leaders thatwould bar admission under the Law of Return to Conservative andReform converts to Judaism.   The poll of 1,096 Israelis, conducted for the American JewishCommittee by the Smith Research Center, a leading Israeli pollingorganization, also found that 51 percent say Reform andConservative rabbis should have the same status in marriages,divorce and conversion that Orthodox rabbis now have.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About 500 members of the National ReligiousBroadcasters have not affirmed its new standards on ethics andfinancial integrity, according to syndicated religion columnistMichael McManus.   Only 70 members have done so, he says. In addition, he writes,the Internal Revenue Service is investigating 23 media evangelists,six of them prominent television preachers.</TEXT><DATELINE>NOTRE DAME, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A gift of $33 million has been given tothe University of Notre Dame, the largest it has ever received, bya businessman-alumnus, Edward J. DeBartolo of Youngstown, Ohio.</TEXT><DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Pope John Paul II and the Archbishop ofCanterbury Robert Runcie, leader of world Anglicanism, have tradedsome more arguments about ordaining women.   Letters between the two prelates were released at a meeting hereof the primates of Anglican branches in 27 nations.   Runcie had written the pope, urging study of the ordinationissue on an ecumenical basis, saying it hasn't even been tried andexpressing hope it would be carried out with ``trust and mutualrespect.''   The pope said ordination of women in some parts of Anglicanismnseems to ``effectively block'' mutual recognition of ministries,since Roman Catholicism and Eastern Orthodoxy are ``firmlyopposed'' to it.   However, the pope emphasized the ``strong bond of communion bywhich we are already united'' and their mutual commitment toincreasing that bond.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs May 19</NOTE></DOC>